## TL;DR: What Every Old Mine Cut Buyer Must Know First

The old mine cushion cut diamond is not a style choice — it is a historical artefact. Every old mine cut on the market today was cut before 1920 by a craftsman working under candlelight, without mathematical optimisation, without computer guidance, and without the mechanical precision that defines every diamond cut after 1919. There will never be new old mine cuts. The supply is finite and shrinking.

**Contrarian Truth — The Old Mine Window:** The most visually distinctive feature of an old mine cut is what most buyers initially mistake for a flaw. The large open culet — the flat bottom facet — creates a visible circle or octagon when the stone is viewed from above, as if looking through a window in the center of the diamond. This is not a defect. It is the signature of hand-cut antique geometry that cannot be replicated by modern cutting equipment. A buyer who wants a modern brilliant with an antique label will be permanently disappointed. A buyer who understands the window for what it is — proof of age and hand-craftsmanship — finds it one of the stone's most compelling features.

**Live price snapshot (estate market {{year}}):**
- Old mine cut 1ct H-J / VS2-SI1: **$1,800–$2,800** (estate dealers)
- Old mine cut 1.5ct H-J / VS2-SI1: **$3,200–$5,500** (estate dealers)
- Old mine cut 2ct H-J / VS2-SI1: **$6,500–$9,500** (estate and auction)
- Modern cushion 1ct natural H / SI1 equivalent: **[from ~$1,900 at Blue Nile](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&caratMin=0.9&caratMax=1.1&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**

**→ The decision that matters most** before buying an old mine cut: request the GIA dossier (not just a vendor description), view the culet size under 10x magnification, and buy from a dealer who photographs the stone face-up under daylight AND candlelight. The Estate Premium is real — you will pay 20–40% above an equivalent modern cushion — and it is only worth paying when you can see and verify what makes the stone antique.

