## What Is an Old Mine Cushion Cut Diamond?

An old mine cushion cut diamond is a hand-cut diamond produced primarily between the Georgian era (1714–1837) and the early Edwardian period (ending roughly 1910–1920), characterised by its high crown, small table, large open culet, and soft square-to-rectangular outline. It is the direct ancestor of both the old European cut and the modern cushion modified brilliant — but it predates both and differs from both in ways that are immediately visible to anyone who examines the stone carefully.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. Old mine cut diamonds occupy a unique position in {{year}} — they are simultaneously the most historically significant diamond cut available and the most misunderstood. Buyers new to antique diamonds often approach old mine cuts expecting a vintage version of a modern brilliant. What they encounter instead is a fundamentally different stone with different proportions, different light behaviour, and different visual character.

The name "old mine" refers not to a specific cut standard but to the origin mines: the diamond mines of Brazil and the Golconda mines of India, active before the discovery of South African deposits in the 1870s. Diamonds cut from these earlier sources were shaped according to the rough crystal, cut to preserve weight rather than maximise brilliance, and finished by eye under candlelight — the only consistent light source available to diamond cutters before the 20th century.

Full credentials and methodology at **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**.

