## The Old Mine Window

The Old Mine Window is the defining geometric feature of every genuine old mine cut diamond — and the single characteristic most likely to confuse a first-time buyer.

![Old mine cut diamond proportions diagram showing high crown, small table, and open culet creating the window effect compared to a modern cushion brilliant](/images/old-mine-cut-diamond-proportions.avif)

The window forms because of the old mine cut's large open culet. In a modern brilliant, the culet is either a point or a tiny facet invisible to the naked eye. In an old mine cut, the culet is a broad, flat facet — sometimes 1.5–2mm across on a 1ct stone — that acts as a lens at the base of the stone. When you look through the table (the top flat facet) of an old mine cut, you see straight through the bottom of the stone to whatever surface is beneath. In a modern brilliant, internal reflections prevent this transparency. In an old mine cut, the geometry creates a visible "window" at the center of the stone — a circle of transparency surrounded by the brilliant facet pattern.

**Why the window exists.** Pre-1920 cutters did not have the mathematical tools (the Tolkowsky ideal cut formula was published in 1919) or the mechanical precision to cut perfectly converging bottom facets. The large culet preserved weight from the rough crystal and was standard practice. Every old mine cut has one. Its size varies — small culets (rated "Very Small" by GIA) create a subtle window effect; large culets (rated "Large" or "Very Large") create a pronounced visual opening.

**The window is not a flaw.** Modern grading penalises cut symmetry and culet size because modern standards optimise for daylight brilliance. Old mine cuts were not designed for fluorescent office lighting or sunlight. They were designed for candlelight — warm, directional, flickering — and in that environment, the window effect disappears entirely. The high crown and steep pavilion angles of an old mine cut create dramatic fire (colour dispersion) under point-source light that a modern brilliant cannot match. Under candlelight at dinner, a well-cut old mine diamond outperforms its modern equivalent on pure visual drama.

**Evaluating the window before purchase.** Request face-up photographs of the stone in both daylight and candlelight from every estate dealer you consider. A stone with a very large culet that looks windowy and lifeless in all lighting conditions may be a genuine old mine cut but not a flattering one. A stone where the window is subtle in daylight and disappears entirely under warm directional light is the ideal old mine cut purchase.

