## Old Mine Cut vs Modern Cushion: The Technical Differences

The old mine cut and the modern cushion modified brilliant share a common ancestor — the original cushion shape — but they diverge fundamentally in proportions, performance, and visual character.

![Side-by-side comparison of old mine cut versus modern cushion modified brilliant showing crown height, table size, and culet differences](/images/old-mine-cushion-vs-modern-cushion.avif)

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Old Mine Cut Advantage</th><th>Modern Cushion Advantage</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Fire (colour dispersion)</td><td>Superior — high crown creates strong dispersion under point-source light</td><td>Lower fire, more consistent white brilliance</td></tr><tr><td>Brightness</td><td>Lower — some light leaks through culet</td><td>Superior — optimised light return across all angles</td></tr><tr><td>Scintillation pattern</td><td>Larger, slower-moving flashes</td><td>Smaller, faster, more numerous flashes</td></tr><tr><td>Performance in daylight</td><td>Moderate — window effect visible</td><td>Superior — maximum brightness in all lighting</td></tr><tr><td>Performance in candlelight</td><td>Superior — comes alive dramatically</td><td>Adequate but less dramatic</td></tr><tr><td>Character and uniqueness</td><td>Every stone is unique — hand-cut variation</td><td>Standardised and consistent</td></tr><tr><td>Certification</td><td>GIA grades but assigns no cut grade</td><td>Full GIA cut grade available (Excellent to Poor)</td></tr><tr><td>Availability</td><td>Finite estate supply only</td><td>New stones cut continuously</td></tr><tr><td>Price predictability</td><td>High variability — estate market pricing</td><td>Transparent BN/retailer pricing</td></tr></tbody></table>

The practical implication: if your priority is maximum brilliance in all lighting conditions, verified by a GIA cut grade, available in a wide size range, buyable from a transparent retailer with return policy — buy a modern cushion from Blue Nile. If your priority is historical character, unique visual identity, warm lighting performance, and ownership of a pre-1920 artefact that cannot be reproduced — buy an old mine cut from an estate dealer.

These are not competing products with a clear winner. They are different objects serving different buyers.

