## The Estate Premium

The Estate Premium is the price differential between a genuine old mine cushion cut diamond and a comparable modern cushion brilliant on the open market — and it is larger, and more volatile, than most buyers expect before entering the antique diamond market.

The baseline measurement: an old mine cut diamond in H-J colour and VS2-SI1 clarity at 1 carat will sell for roughly 20–40% more than an equivalent modern natural cushion of the same weight and quality grade at a major retailer. At 2ct and above, the premium often reaches 40–60% over new equivalents because the supply of clean, well-proportioned antique stones above 2ct is genuinely scarce.

![The Estate Premium chart showing old mine cut diamond price vs modern cushion price across carat weights from 0.75ct to 3ct with the premium gap annotated](/images/old-mine-cut-estate-premium.avif)

**Why The Estate Premium exists.** Three forces drive it. First, scarcity: no new old mine cuts are being produced, and the existing estate supply diminishes as stones are lost, damaged, or recut into modern shapes. Second, collector demand: antique diamond collectors actively bid for large, well-preserved old mine cuts, competing with engagement ring buyers and pushing prices above retail equivalents. Third, provenance value: a documented old mine cut with a traceable estate history commands additional premium at auction beyond the stone's intrinsic characteristics.

**Where The Estate Premium is largest.** Certified stones at major auction houses (Sotheby's, Christie's, Bonhams) carry the highest premiums — typically 30–50% above comparable modern loose diamonds, plus buyer's premiums of 15–25% on top of the hammer price. Private estate dealer sales carry smaller premiums (15–30%) but involve higher trust risk without a major house's authentication backing. Online estate marketplaces (1stDibs, Worthy) show wide price variation — The Estate Premium is present but inconsistently applied depending on the seller's expertise and the stone's documentation.

**When The Estate Premium is not worth paying.** An old mine cut diamond sold without GIA documentation, without face-up photography in multiple lighting conditions, and without a clear chain of custody offers a premium for uncertainty rather than for genuine antique value. The premium is only justified when you can verify: (1) the stone is genuinely pre-1920 cut, (2) the culet and proportions match the old mine cut standard, (3) the colour and clarity grades are independently confirmed.

