## Old Mine Cut Diamond Certification

GIA certifies old mine cut diamonds but grades them differently from modern cuts. Understanding this difference is essential before evaluating any old mine cut GIA report.

**What GIA does grade for old mine cuts:**
- Carat weight (same as any diamond)
- Colour grade (D through Z and Fancy scale)
- Clarity grade (FL through I3)
- Shape description: "Old Mine Brilliant" in the Cut section

**What GIA does NOT grade for old mine cuts:**
- Cut grade (no Excellent / Very Good / Good assignment)
- Polish and symmetry grades are assigned but carry different meaning than for modern cuts
- Proportions are measured and reported but not scored

**Why no cut grade matters.** The absence of a cut grade is not a negative — it accurately reflects the reality that old mine cut geometry cannot be evaluated against the same standards as modern brilliants. A stone graded "Very Good" for polish and symmetry on a GIA old mine cut report is a high-quality antique stone; those grades refer to the craftsmanship of the original cutting, not performance versus an ideal-cut standard.

**The culet notation.** GIA's old mine cut reports describe culet size as: None, Very Small, Small, Medium, Slightly Large, Large, Very Large, or Extremely Large. For buying purposes: Very Small to Small culets create the most modern-looking old mine cuts (window effect minimal). Large to Very Large culets are most characteristic of the period but most visually distinctive in daylight. Choose based on how much you value authenticity versus everyday visual appeal.

**Colour in old mine cuts.** Old mine cuts were cut to preserve rough crystal weight rather than maximise colour purity. Most period old mine cuts fall in the G–L colour range, with K–M being very common in Victorian-era stones. This is not a flaw — the warm tones of an L-colour old mine cut in yellow gold look entirely intentional and aesthetically coherent. The modern preference for D-G colour grades did not exist when these stones were cut.

