## Old Mine Cut Diamond Engagement Rings

Setting an old mine cushion cut diamond in an engagement ring requires choosing a mounting that respects the stone's era and its proportions — particularly the high crown and the larger culet footprint at the base.

**Four-prong yellow gold solitaire.** The most historically accurate choice for a Victorian or Georgian old mine cut. Four prongs (not six) were the standard setting for this period's cushion-shaped stones, and 18K or 22K yellow gold was the near-universal metal choice. A simple four-prong yellow gold solitaire with a plain shank is the setting closest to original period intent — it places no visual competition around the stone and lets the old mine cut's fire and character dominate.

**Milgrain and filigree settings.** Edwardian-era old mine cuts were frequently set in filigree platinum or white gold with milgrain beading along all edges — a delicate, lace-like style that complemented the stone's soft geometry perfectly. For a buyer who wants an old mine cut in a lighter, more intricate mounting than a solitaire, an Edwardian-inspired milgrain setting is the most period-appropriate choice.

**Halo settings for old mine cuts.** A cushion halo around an old mine cut diamond creates a modern aesthetic with antique stone character. The halo must be designed with the old mine cut's rounded outline in mind — a perfectly geometric modern halo will fight the slight irregularity of the antique stone. Choose halos with softer outlines, milgrain edges, and round brilliant melee (not princess cut) to blend with the old mine cut's organic geometry. For modern cushion halo options as a comparison baseline: [Blue Nile cushion halo rings](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&SettingID=Halo&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

**Bezel settings.** A bezel enclosure around an old mine cut creates a modern, architectural look that contrasts intentionally with the antique stone. This is a valid aesthetic choice for buyers who want an antique stone in a contemporary setting. The bezel also provides the most practical protection for the stone's slightly rounded girdle, which lacks the precise girdle consistency of modern cuts.

**Sizing and prong placement.** Old mine cuts have a higher crown than modern cushions — the stone sits taller above the finger. Standard modern settings designed for cushion modified brilliants may need adjustment to accommodate this additional height. Work with a setter who has experience with antique stones. Prong tips that work on a 14% crown modern cushion may not engage properly with a 42% crown old mine cut.

---

## Georgian and Victorian Old Mine Diamonds: What to Know

Old mine cut diamonds span three significant periods of jewellery history. The era of a stone affects both its characteristics and its market value.

**Georgian era (1714–1837).** The earliest old mine cuts were set exclusively in yellow gold or silver (silver for the collet — the setting — backing gold for the shank). Georgian jewellery was made without mechanical assistance; every setting was hand-fabricated. Foil backing was used behind stones to enhance brilliance — a technique that would never be applied to modern stones but is entirely period-accurate in Georgian pieces. Genuine Georgian jewellery with intact original settings is extremely rare and commands significant premiums at auction. GIA certification of the stone is harder to obtain because removing a Georgian stone from its setting risks damaging the mount.

**Victorian era (1837–1901).** The most abundant source of old mine cut diamonds on the estate market today. Queen Victoria's long reign coincided with the South African diamond discovery of 1870, which flooded the market with affordable diamonds and drove widespread use in jewellery. Victorian old mine cuts are available in the widest range of sizes and qualities. The Sentimental period (1837–1860) features heavy gold work; the Grand period (1860–1885) shows larger, more formal pieces; the Aesthetic period (1885–1900) moves toward lighter, more naturalistic designs. Victorian period attribution adds collector value but requires jewellery expertise to authenticate.

**Edwardian era (1901–1910).** The transition period between old mine cuts and old European cuts (which appeared circa 1900–1910 before the modern brilliant took over). Edwardian jewellery features platinum or white gold, filigree work, and both old mine and early old European stones. If you are specifically seeking an old mine cut rather than an old European cut, verify the culet size and crown angle — Edwardian pieces may contain either cut style.

---

## Metal Choice for Old Mine Cut Rings

**Yellow gold.** The historically correct choice for Georgian and Victorian old mine cuts. Yellow gold's warm colour flatters the warmer colour grades (J–M) common in period stones, and the gold's reflectivity under directional light amplifies the old mine cut's fire characteristics. 18K yellow gold is the most period-accurate alloy for Victorian pieces; 22K appears in the earliest Georgian-era work.

**Rose gold.** A particularly flattering choice for old mine cuts in the K–M colour range. The rosy warmth of rose gold is visually coherent with a slightly warm-toned old mine cut and creates a unified colour story across stone and metal. Rose gold old mine cut rings have become one of the most popular vintage-inspired engagement ring styles in {{year}}.

**Platinum.** Platinum settings for old mine cuts are historically accurate only for the Edwardian period (1901–1910) and later. Platinum used with a pre-1900 old mine cut is an anachronistic pairing — not wrong visually, but not period-correct. For buyers who want a modern setting for an antique stone, platinum is a valid choice; for buyers who prioritise historical authenticity, yellow gold is the appropriate choice for Victorian and Georgian stones.

**White gold.** The most common modern choice for old mine cuts set in contemporary mountings. White gold's neutral colour creates maximum contrast with the stone, allowing the old mine cut's distinctive visual character to dominate without metal colour interference. Rhodium plating of white gold settings will eventually wear, exposing the slightly warm undertone of 14K white gold alloy.

