## Old Mine Cut vs Modern Cushion: The Buyer's Decision

The choice between an old mine cut and a modern cushion brilliant reduces to three binary questions.

**Do you need a GIA cut grade?** If yes, buy modern. GIA does not assign cut grades to old mine cuts. If a stone's objectively graded cutting performance is important to you — if you are comparing multiple diamonds on measurable cut performance — you need a modern cushion.

**Do you value character over consistency?** Modern cushion brilliants are optimised for consistent daylight performance. Every well-cut modern cushion performs predictably well. Old mine cuts vary — some are extraordinarily beautiful under all lighting, others are best seen by candlelight only. If you are comfortable with the variability of a hand-cut stone and see that variability as part of the appeal, old mine cuts reward the search. If you want guaranteed performance from a stated quality, buy modern.

**Are you buying for the stone or the story?** A modern cushion cut is a high-performance gemstone. An old mine cut is a gemstone with history — made before the First World War, shaped by hand, survived intact through a century or more of wear and estate dispersal. For buyers for whom that history matters and adds value, The Estate Premium is a reasonable price of admission. For buyers who want maximum diamond per dollar, modern natural or lab cushion cuts offer better value per carat.

